snippet.textDisplay: the sensor size isn't what gives that blur on the background! Its the aperture. (the opening in the lens) make it bigger the background gets blurry make it smaller the brightness goes down and the background gets sharper. The S8 has an f/1.7 aperture which is REALLY wide. Its why it's so good at low light photos the hole is wide open letting tonnes of light in. It's also why Samsung put the duel aperture on the S9 and upwards, You can choose f/2.4 which will have sharper backgrounds than f/1.7

snippet.textDisplay:
I think that the lack of blur on the Note 10/S10E isn't primarily due to the size of the sensors but to the fact that when taking a picture with strong light, the aperture goes down to 2.4 instead of 1.5. However, other phones does not have this capability and the aperture will stay higher despite the light and therefore the background will be blurrier.
So in conclusion the lack of bokeh is due to a Samsung technology that is not yet available on other smartphones.

snippet.textDisplay: Blur in photos needs to go. It works in movies and games because your eyes only focus on the subject of the image. In a photo, you have time to look around and everything around the subject looks bad. Its true that your eyes blur backgrounds, but only when you don't look at them. If you look at the background it gets focused. Unless you intentionally focus your mind away from your center of vision, you don't notice blur with normal vision. That is why the blurred photos look worse, it doesn't look natural if you take your eyes off of the subject at all.

snippet.textDisplay: I don't know why the hate about how one "better" camera should somehow win this personal preference contest. The type of photo matters, and what people want to see from that photo is probably how this came about. In the first, it's obvious the focus should be on the person. If a brighter image is what's going to show me the person better, then I'll take that image. The second with the hot sauce is similar as in I'm not caring about the other more neutral subjects in the background. The third one shouldn't become such a surprise. Obviously, the car is the focus, but you also subjected that item with colorful more interesting items throughout the piece. I saw the vibrant color board, some fancy red sneakers, a pinkly detailed camo backpack, the speckled details of the navy shirt and more. If I can see more with little or no interference of the main subject matter (the red car), then I'll take the additional detail of the background. That's just my preference I guess. I'm not surprised.
